{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01JppMcNVywmdEwXLRssrSte","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"This is a test plan design task for a CI/CD pipeline lint step. I need to analyze each behavior and determine:\n1. The minimum test level needed to catch real failures\n2. A test description that would actually catch the failure\n3. Whether the plan is consistent (test actually requires that level)\n4. Confidence probabilities for each level\n\nLet me work through each behavior:\n\n## Behavior 1: Only files changed in the PR are analyzed\n\n**Behavior**: \"Only files changed in the pull request are analyzed — unchanged files are not scanned.\"\n\n**Key questions**:\n- MOCK-MISS: Could a pure in-process mock miss this? The system needs to:\n  - Get the list of changed files from GitHub API or Git\n  - Filter files to analyze based on this list\n  - Verify only those files are analyzed\n  \n  A mock that returns a file list could hide failures in actual Git interaction or GitHub API. If the code has a bug like \"always scanning all files despite the filter\", a unit test with mocked GitHub API would still pass if it doesn't actually verify Git behavior.\n\n- REAL-INFRA: Does it depend on real Git or GitHub API? Yes - to determine what files changed, you need either:\n  - Real Git checkout state to run `git diff`\n  - Real GitHub API to get PR diff\n  \n- MOCK-HIDE: Would mocking always pass? If you mock the \"get changed files\" function to return a fixed list, the test wouldn't verify that the actual Git/GitHub integration works correctly.\n\n**Minimum Level**: Integration\n- Need a real Git checkout with actual file changes, or a real GitHub API interaction, or at least a filesystem with actual files and a real Git command execution\n- Can't be Unit because Git is a subprocess/external system\n- Could be tested with a local Git repo (Integration) without needing System-level GitHub API\n\n**Test Description**: \n\"Create a local Git repository with multiple files. \n\nMake changes to exactly 3 files, commit them, and create a mock PR context pointing to these changed files. Run the linter and verify that:\n1. Only the 3 changed files appear in the analysis results\n2. All other files in the repo are NOT analyzed\n3. The analysis report lists exactly 3 files\"\n\nThis requires Integration because it needs real filesystem + Git, not just mocked function calls.\n\n## Behavior 2: Findings grouped by severity\n\n**Behavior**: \"Findings are grouped by severity (error, warning, info) in the posted PR comment.\"\n\n**Key questions**:\n- MOCK-MISS: Could a pure mock miss this? The system needs to format findings by severity level and structure them in the comment output. A mock that just verifies \"a comment was posted\" wouldn't catch if the grouping logic is broken or if the formatting is wrong.\n\n- REAL-INFRA: Does it depend on real GitHub API? Yes - posting to GitHub requires actual API calls, though the grouping logic itself could be tested at Unit level if isolated.\n\n- MOCK-HIDE: Would mocking always pass? If you mock the GitHub API call, you'd miss failures in how the comment is actually formatted or posted.\n\n**Minimum Level**: Integration\n- Need to verify the actual comment structure posted to GitHub, or at minimum test the formatting logic with real output that would be posted\n- Unit tests could verify the grouping algorithm in isolation, but wouldn't catch formatting or API integration issues\n\n**Test Description**: \n\"Generate findings with mixed severities (5 errors, 3 warnings, 2 info messages). Run the linter and verify the posted comment groups findings by severity with proper headers and formatting for each group.\" The grouping logic itself is a pure function—given findings with severity levels, it transforms them into organized sections. Testing this in isolation requires mocking the linter output and GitHub API, making it Unit-level. The actual posting to GitHub would be a separate System-level concern.\n\nFor the test, I'd create mixed findings (5 errors, 3 warnings, 2 info) and verify they're correctly bucketed into their respective sections, maintain order within each group, and appear in the right sequence (errors first, then warnings, then info).\n\nNow for the performance behavior: a 200-file PR needs to complete within the 10-minute GitHub Actions timeout. This can't be tested with mocks—if I mock the linter to return instantly, I'll miss real timing bottlenecks. The test depends on actual file processing speed and system constraints, so it requires System-level testing with real or realistic linter execution against a genuine 200-file workload to measure elapsed time accurately. When the linter encounters a malformed file and crashes, it should still process the remaining files and return results. A mock wouldn't catch this since it could skip the crash scenario entirely. The real subprocess needs to actually fail on the malformed input, and the error handling must work correctly to continue analyzing other files. This requires running the actual linter process against a file designed to trigger a crash, then verifying the remaining files were still analyzed.\n\nFor deduplication, when multiple overlapping rules flag the same issue on a single line, those duplicate findings should be consolidated in the output. Mocks could mask this behavior if they don't return overlapping results.\n\nThe deduplication itself is a deterministic transformation—given duplicate findings with matching file, line, and rule identifiers, remove the extras. This could be tested at Unit level with mocked findings, or at Integration level by running actual overlapping rules to see if duplicates naturally emerge and get properly removed.\n\nThe key question is whether the behavior requires testing real rule interactions or just the dedup logic in isolation. Since the core functionality is a pure function that doesn't depend on how the rules are implemented, Unit testing with realistic mock data seems sufficient. However, if the intent is to verify that overlapping rules actually produce duplicates in practice, Integration testing would be more appropriate. The deduplication logic itself is pure data transformation, so I can test it at the unit level by passing in duplicate findings and verifying one is kept while non-duplicates remain untouched. Integration testing would confirm this works with actual overlapping rules, but the core logic doesn't require that.\n\nFor the test, I'd create findings where two rules flag the same line identically, run them through deduplication, and verify duplicates are removed while keeping one representative finding and preserving findings on different lines.\n\nNow considering confidence levels for each behavior—how likely each test level would catch a real failure. For the changed files behavior, unit testing has low confidence since the actual file filtering depends on the system's file discovery mechanism. The core question is whether we're testing just the filtering logic itself or the entire flow including PR detection. Since the behavior explicitly mentions \"files changed in the pull request,\" we need to verify that PR context detection actually works, not just mock it away. This pushes us toward Integration or System level.\n\nFor the probability split, Integration makes sense if we're using local Git to simulate changed files, while System applies if we're hitting the actual GitHub API. The minimum viable test would likely use Integration—mocking the GitHub context but running real Git operations to confirm the filtering works end-to-end.\n\nBehavior 2 is primarily about the grouping logic itself, which is pure and testable at Unit level with mocked findings. The GitHub posting is a side effect, not the core behavior being validated. Behavior 3 is unambiguously System—we need real file I/O, actual linter execution, and genuine timing measurements to verify the 10-minute constraint. No mock can adequately substitute for that.\n\nBehavior 4 involves subprocess crash handling, which requires real process execution to properly test. While we could mock a crash at Integration level with a local subprocess, validating actual crash behavior demands System-level testing. Behavior 5 is straightforward Unit testing since deduplication operates on structured data with pure logic.\n\nFor the consistency check: Behavior 1's Integration level matches its test description requiring real Git and filesystem operations. Behavior 2's Unit level aligns with testing pure severity logic. Behavior 3's System level fits the requirement for real subprocess execution with 200 files and actual linter invocation.\n\nBehavior 4 correctly uses System level to handle real subprocess crashes. Behavior 5 appropriately stays at Unit level for mocked findings logic. All five behaviors align with their chosen test levels.\n\nReconsidering Behavior 3 though—the 10-minute completion requirement could potentially be validated at Integration level by creating 200 local files and running the actual linter subprocess. A System-level test would run in the GitHub Actions environment itself. The Integration approach would catch most failures since it exercises real files and the real linter, but might miss environment-specific issues that only surface in GitHub Actions due to resource constraints or timing differences.\n\nSince the behavior explicitly references the \"10-minute Actions timeout,\" System testing seems more aligned with the stated requirement. However, Integration testing would realistically catch the majority of performance regressions. Adjusting the weights: Integration gets 0.20 for catching most practical failures, System gets 0.75 for GitHub Actions specificity, with Unit, Agentic, and Workflow at 0.02, 0.01, and 0.02 respectively.\n\nThe \"GitHub Actions timeout\" phrasing might just be context rather than a mandate to test within that environment. The core failure—analysis exceeding 10 minutes on 200 files—is testable locally at Integration level.\n\nFor the behavior justifications: PR file detection requires Git or GitHub API interaction, making it Integration-dependent. Grouping findings by severity is pure data transformation that works with mocked linter output, so it's Unit-testable. Performance on 200 files demands actual file I/O and subprocess execution with real timing measurements.\n\nLinter crash handling needs a genuine subprocess failure to verify error recovery continues processing remaining files. Duplicate deduplication logic operates on finding structures and can be validated with mock data containing known duplicates.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13468,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13468},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f0b697f3-b5c1-4e5b-a6ad-e1351411d2c6","uuid":"ab0f9d9f-6c40-40fe-93f6-9f2491907042"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01JppMcNVywmdEwXLRssrSte","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Looking at this CI/CD lint pipeline issue, I need to determine the minimum test infrastructure for each behavior by considering where real failures would actually manifest.\n\nLet me work through each behavior systematically:\n\n**Behavior 1: Only changed files analyzed**\n- The system must detect which files changed in a PR (via Git diff or GitHub API) and filter to those\n- Mocking the file-list would skip testing the actual change detection\n- Real failure: PR detection breaks, all files get scanned instead\n- Minimum: **Integration** (need real Git state or GitHub PR context)\n\n**Behavior 2: Findings grouped by severity**\n- This is pure data transformation: findings → grouped findings\n- The grouping logic itself has no I/O dependencies\n- Real failure: output grouping is wrong (wrong sections, missing findings)\n- Minimum: **Unit** (pure logic on structured data)\n\n**Behavior 3: 200 files within 10 minutes**\n- Performance depends on real file I/O, real linter subprocess, real timing\n- Mocking the linter would hide timeout failures completely\n- Real failure: linter is too slow on realistic workload\n- Minimum: **System** (subprocess execution + timing measurement required)\n\n**Behavior 4: Crash recovery**\n- Must handle actual subprocess failure and continue processing\n- Mocking a crash would skip testing real error handling\n- Real failure: subprocess crashes and stops analyzing remaining files\n- Minimum: **System** (need real subprocess crash + error recovery)\n\n**Behavior 5: Deduplication of overlapping rules**\n- Dedup is pure logic on findings structures\n- Takes a list with duplicates, produces deduplicated list\n- Real failure: duplicates slip through to output\n- Minimum: **Unit** (pure logic on structured data)"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13468,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13468},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f0b697f3-b5c1-4e5b-a6ad-e1351411d2c6","uuid":"f0d2146e-da2b-43bd-8fb7-650d0050a9fc"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01JppMcNVywmdEwXLRssrSte","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01YGWZXLKUsSgfwnHNUj2xpJ","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Only files changed in the pull request are analyzed — unchanged files are not scanned","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Must verify that PR file detection (via Git diff or GitHub API) works correctly and filtering excludes non-changed files. Mocking the file-list detection would hide failures in the actual Git or GitHub integration. Requires real filesystem state or GitHub PR context to detect changes.","test_description":"Create a local Git repository with 10 files. Stage, commit, and designate them as baseline. Modify exactly 3 of those files. Run the linter in a mock PR context where changed files = [file1, file3, file7]. Verify: (1) analysis results mention exactly 3 files, (2) the 7 unchanged files do not appear in results or logs, (3) analysis skipped scanning the unchanged files.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Findings are grouped by severity (error, warning, info) in the posted PR comment","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Grouping is pure data transformation with no I/O: findings-with-severities → grouped findings. Can test by mocking linter output and mock GitHub API calls, verifying the comment body contains the correct structure. Real failure would be incorrect grouping (mixed severities, wrong order, lost findings), all detectable in output structure without real linter or real GitHub.","test_description":"Create a test set of findings: 5 errors, 3 warnings, 2 info-level messages. Pass through the grouping-and-formatting function. Verify: (1) comment body has three sections in order [errors, warnings, info], (2) all 5 errors appear in errors section, (3) all 3 warnings in warnings section, (4) all 2 info in info section, (5) within each section, order matches input order, (6) no findings are lost or duplicated across sections.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.75,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"A pull request that touches 200 files completes analysis within the 10-minute Actions timeout","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Performance behavior requires real file I/O (200 files on disk), real linter subprocess execution, and actual timing measurement. Mocking the linter would hide timeout failures entirely—the mock returns instantly, so the test would pass even if the real linter times out. Must run against realistic 200-file workload with real subprocess to catch performance regressions.","test_description":"Generate or load 200 files with realistic code (mix of sizes, LOC, complexity). Run the actual linter subprocess on all 200 files. Use system timer to measure wall-clock elapsed time from start to final result posting. Verify: (1) total elapsed time < 600 seconds, (2) all 200 files appear in analysis results, (3) no files were skipped or timed out individually, (4) subprocess completed successfully with non-zero exit only on actual errors, not timeouts.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.78,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When the linter process crashes on a malformed file, the remaining files are still analyzed and results posted","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Behavior depends on subprocess-level crash handling: a real linter process must fail, and the orchestrator must recover and continue. Mocking the linter or mocking the crash would skip the actual error handling path. Real failure: subprocess crashes → orchestrator stops → remaining files are not analyzed. Requires real subprocess interaction and error handling in the actual execution environment.","test_description":"Create a set of 10 files. One file is intentionally malformed (syntax that causes linter to crash; e.g., binary garbage). Run the linter as a real subprocess on all 10 files. Verify: (1) subprocess exits with non-zero code or crash signal, (2) the 9 well-formed files are still analyzed and findings appear in results, (3) the malformed file is logged with an error message, (4) final results include data from the 9 good files, (5) analysis did not halt—comment was still posted to PR.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.76,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Duplicate findings on the same line from overlapping rules are deduplicated in the output","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Deduplication is pure data-structure logic: takes findings with potential duplicates (same file, line, rule) and removes duplicates. No I/O, no external dependencies. Can be tested by constructing mock findings with known duplicates and verifying output. Real failure would be duplicates in the output, detectable by comparing input and output structures without running real rules or linter.","test_description":"Create a findings list where two different rule engines flag the same line of the same file with identical findings (same message, same severity). Include 10 total findings: 3 unique, 2 pairs of duplicates (4 duplicate entries), and 3 more unique. Pass through deduplication function. Verify: (1) duplicates are removed, leaving 8 findings total, (2) for each duplicate pair, exactly one copy is retained, (3) non-duplicate findings are all present, (4) findings on different lines are not affected by dedup.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.8,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"ca